x which contains the success flags for each mix. So `len(success) > 0` means at 
least one item was completed. This is probably fine for event publishing.\n\n4. 
**`EventDispatchServer.dispatch` in `internal/server/wcore/wcc/event_dispatch_se
rver.go`**: On line 92, `err := e.routers.Router(event.EventType)(...)` and then
it publishes the event regardless of whether `err` is nil or not. The publish ha
ppens in a goroutine. More importantly, if `e.publisher` is nil it skips, which 
is good. But `publishEvent` is called even when the router returns an error - is
this intended? The event name says "dispatch" so maybe yes, but this could be a 
design concern. Not a blocking issue.\n\n5. **In `internal/pkg/eventbus/bus.go` 
line 66-74**: `b.pool.Go(func() { h(ctx, event) })` - the handler runs in a goro
utine pool but `ctx` is captured from the outer scope. Since `h` and `ctx` are l
oop variables that are reused, but they\'re passed by value (h is a func value, 
ctx is an interface value), and the goroutine starts immediately, this is actual
ly safe in this specific case because the loop body doesn\'t continue before the
goroutine is submitted. Actually wait - `h` and `ctx` are re-assigned on each it
eration but the closure captures them. However, since `b.pool.Go` should execute
the closure immediately (just queue it), and Go closures capture variables by re
ference, there IS a race condition! If the pool has limited capacity and queues 
the function, by the time it runs `h` and `ctx` and `event` may have changed.\n\
nWait, looking at `gopool.Go` - it should immediately capture the variables on t
he current goroutine\'s stack before scheduling. Let me check... Actually `gopoo
l` from bytedance typically copies the closure and executes it on another gorout
ine. The closure captures variables by reference. So yes, this is a data race.\n
